## Linux Command-Line Fundamentals

Overview
This project documents my practical learning of Linux command-line fundamentals, with a focus on file system navigation and basic file management.
These skills form a core foundation for SOC Analysts and Network Security Analysts, as Linux is widely used in servers, security tools, and log management systems.
All commands were practiced hands-on in a Linux environment to build confidence and accuracy.

---

## File System Navigation & Management

** pwd ‚Äî Print Working Directory **
The pwd command displays the absolute path of the current working directory.
Purpose:
Confirms the exact location within the file system
Helps prevent running commands in the wrong directory
cd ‚Äî Change Directory
The cd command is used to move between directories within the Linux file system.
Examples include using cd logs to enter a directory, cd .. to move one level up to the parent directory, and cd without arguments to return to the home directory.
Key understanding:
cd without arguments moves to the home directory
cd .. moves one directory level up
ls ‚Äî List Directory Contents
The ls command displays files and directories within a specified location.
Common options include ls -l for a detailed view showing permissions, ownership, file size, and timestamps, and ls -a for displaying hidden files.
Security relevance:
Useful for checking file ownership and permissions
Commonly used when inspecting system and log directories
touch ‚Äî Create Files
The touch command creates empty files or updates timestamps of existing files, such as using touch alert.txt to create a new file.
Use case:
Creating test files or configuration placeholders
rm ‚Äî Remove Files and Directories
The rm command deletes files and directories from the system.
For example, rm test.log removes a file, while rm -r test recursively removes a directory and its contents.
Important notes:
Files removed using rm are permanently deleted
Recursive deletion is required for directories
Extra caution is necessary when using administrative privileges
mv ‚Äî Move or Rename Files
The mv command is used to move files between directories or rename them.
Examples include mv old.txt new.txt to rename a file and mv alerts.log /var/log/ to move a file into a system log directory.
Security context:
Frequently used when organizing log files
System directories may require elevated permissions
‚ö†Ô∏è Command Safety Awareness
I developed awareness of potentially destructive commands such as rm *.
Key understanding:
Removes all non-hidden files in the current directory
Does not remove directories unless used with the recursive option
Reinforces the importance of verifying the working directory before execution
